<div class="markdown"><h1>Going Neural</h1>
<p>In this part of the tutorial we&#39;ll see how the DifferentialEquations ecosystems can be interfaced with the Lux &#40;and Flux&#41; Deep Learning capabilities.</p>
<p>We will train Neural Networks to approximate a dynamical system &#40;the same we defined in the previous Pluto&#41;.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>We start by loading the necessary libraries</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>using Lux, DiffEqFlux, DifferentialEquations, Optimization, OptimizationOptimJL, Random, Plots</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><h2>Simulate Data</h2>
<p>We create some data for our analysis, setting up an ODE system. For the details of what&#39;s happening here</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    rng = Random.default_rng()
    u‚ÇÄ = Float32[1.0; 1.0]

    Lux.Dense(20,20,tanh),
    Lux.Dense(20, 2)
)</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><p>Next, we build a prediction function that takes the initial values of the system, and the network information &#40;parameters and structure&#41;.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function predict_neuralode(p)
  Array(prob_neuralode(u‚ÇÄ, p, str‚Çô‚Çô)[1])
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-predict_neuralode' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>predict_neuralode (generic function with 1 method)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Define the loss function</h2>
<p>The key step is now to define a loss function. The parameters of the network will be optimized to minimise the loss. The function needs to take two inputs: network params and hyperparameters &#40;that we don&#39;t actually use in our case&#41;.</p>
<p>There&#39;s various way to do it, but we&#39;ll use Julia multiple dispatch defining a method for one argument, and another for two arguments.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function loss_neuralode(network_params)
    pred = predict_neuralode(network_params)
    loss = sum(abs2, true_data .- pred)
    return loss, pred
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-loss_neuralode' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>loss_neuralode (generic function with 1 method)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>loss_neuralode(p,hyper_p) = loss_neuralode(p)</code></pre>
<pre id='var-loss_neuralode' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>loss_neuralode (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Train to Results</h2>
<p>We&#39;re mostly done, now it&#39;s time to traing the network on the synthetic data we produced, plot and enjoy.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function plot_solutions(true_data, prediction)
    plt = plot(tsteps, true_data', label = ["org üê±" "org üòÑ"])
    scatter!(plt, tsteps, prediction',  label = ["pred üê±" "pred üòÑ"])

end</code></pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>callback = function (p, l, pred; doplot = false)
  println(l)
  # plot current prediction against data
  if doplot

      return plt
  end
  return false
end</code></pre>
